ce:section.ce:para:
During hard machining, the production of elevated temperatures is a prominent occurrence in several machining areas. The generation of heat has a detrimental impact on both the cutting instruments and the material being worked on. While the chips may absorb the highest temperature, it still has harmful consequences on both the tool and workpiece. Therefore, in every machining operation, the management of heat generation is a crucial and laborious undertaking [69]. Due to the process of machining, the main zone will experience significant plastic deformation. The frictional force will be present in the secondary zone. Owing to plastic deformation, the temperature experienced a fast rise. The efficacy of different cooling-lubrication methods is assessed by comparing their impact on the cutting temperature. The thermographic pictures (Fig. 16
                        ) depict the cutting temperature across different machining settings. The use of the dry machining technology led to elevated cutting temperatures. In dry turning, the lack of cutting fluid causes increased friction between the tool and workpiece, resulting in the accumulation of heat at the interface. Consequently, the cutting temperature rises. Nevertheless, the oil droplets absorbed a significant amount of latent heat from the tool surfaces, chips, and workpieces during evaporation under SQL. As a consequence, the cutting temperature decreased compared to the dry mode [70]. The implementation of an efficient cooling-lubrication method for CDs has significantly reduced the cutting temperature compared to dry machining and OSQL settings. The CDs augmented convective heat transport in the coolant and boosted thermal conductivity, resulting in more effective heat dissipation from the cutting zone. Furthermore, CDs are more prone to exert a substantial influence on heat transmission and lubrication. The CDs possess the capability to traverse through the pores, offering both cushioning and a ball bearing action. This enhances the contact condition between tool and work surfaces, while also aiding in the decrease of temperature in the machining regions. Utilising LN2 as a coolant provides a thorough remedy for the machining of challenging-to-cut metals. The chosen cooling solution in demanding metalworking applications is characterised by its ultra-low temperature, effective heat absorption, lubricating qualities, and environmental advantages. It ensures improved tool performance and machining outputs. Applying cutting fluid in a mist form creates a thin film protecting cryogenic barrier between the tool and work surface. This improves the tribological property, reducing friction and enhancing heat dissipation in the cutting zone. In addition, when LN2 is applied to the cutting region, it rapidly dissipates by absorption, resulting in an immediate reduction in heat and a noticeable fall in temperature [71]. LN2 cooling reduces thermal deformation and eliminates heat build-up, resulting in smoother surface finish and more precise machining. By reducing thermal deformation and preventing the build-up of heat, the process results in a smoother surface finish and more precise machining. The relationship between cutting temperature and speed was found under different settings, as depicted in Fig. 17
                        . A consistent decrease in cutting temperature was found as the speed increased under all situations. This result can be ascribed to two possible sources. Firstly, it is probable that there will be an increase in friction at the points where the tool comes into contact with the workpiece and the tool comes into contact with the chip. An important situation to contemplate is when an item is in motion at a significant velocity. Under such circumstances, the constrained duration for thermal energy exchange between the item and its environment might provide a difficulty. Furthermore, the inadequate thermal conductivity of the workpiece material prevents the heat from being transferred to the outside, leading to elevated temperatures [72]. Furthermore, the increase in strain rate might perhaps explain the rise in temperature at high velocities. Due to the need for a significant amount of energy to plastically deform the material at fast speeds, and the high cutting energy required for shearing, the resultant temperature is elevated. The sliding velocity of the chip may be a crucial factor in evaluating the cutting temperature. High sliding velocity of chips during dry cutting might lead to increased temperature generation [72]. The impact of feed on temperature was demonstrated in Fig. 17. The experimental findings demonstrated a significant rise in temperature across all four varied cooling settings when the feed rate was altered. This might likely be linked to the substantial interaction between the tool and the workpiece during the machining process. Furthermore, the material removal rate is greatly influenced by the increased input value. Therefore, in the present experimental study, the use of a hard material resulted in the observation of both hard and hot chips throughout the process. Therefore, when the tool and work have a larger contact area, the feed rate increases, resulting in an extended duration of contact between the tool surface and the hard and hot cutting chips. Therefore, when the feed rate rise, the temperature also increased regardless of the cutting conditions.
